'''Oshaku Shrine''' (おしゃくじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in {{ill|lt=Miyake Village|Q1154797|WD=Q1154797|1=Miyake, Tokyo}}, {{ill|lt=Tokyo|Q1490|WD=Q1490|1=Tokyo}}.

=== History ===
Its founding period is unknown. However, because it is identified with the {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286}} '''Sakitamahime-no-Mikoto Shrine''' listed in the {{ill|lt=Engishiki|Q1342448|WD=Q1342448|1=Engishiki}}, it is presumed to have already existed at least during the {{ill|lt=Engi|Q1374325|WD=Q1374325|1=Engi (era)}} era ({{ill|lt=901|Q23580|WD=Q23580|1=901}}–{{ill|lt=923|Q30108|WD=Q30108|1=923}})<ref name="散歩">Tokyo Historical Education Research Society (ed.), ''Historical Walks of Tokyo, Lower Volume (Historical Walks 13): Tama and Islands'', Yamakawa Shuppansha, 2005, p.246.</ref>.

It was originally in the northeast of {{ill|lt=Miyakejima|Q1075076|WD=Q1075076|1=Miyake-jima}}, but in {{ill|lt=1561|Q6618|WD=Q6618|1=1561}} ({{ill|lt=Eishō|Q1193577|WD=Q1193577|1=Eishō (Muromachi period)}} 13) it was moved to its present location<ref name="official">[https://miyakejima-jinja.jimdofree.com/ Top page of Miyakejima shrines] Miyakejima shrines.</ref>.

The shrine priests of this shrine have been inherited for generations by the {{ill|lt=Mibu clan|Q11429506|WD=Q11429506|1=Mibushi}}. The Mibu clan is known as the family that compiled the ''{{ill|lt=Miyake-ki|Q17215100|WD=Q17215100|1=Miyake-ki}}'', which records the origins of the {{ill|lt=Izu Islands|Q864302|WD=Q864302|1=Izu Islands}}.

The shrine has many merged shrines, including several shikinaisha. In addition to the annual grand festival on October 10, in mid-July the Gozu Tennō Festival (so-called {{ill|lt=Gion Festival|Q979873|WD=Q979873|1=Gion Matsuri}}), derived from one merged shrine, {{ill|lt=Gozu Tennō|Q11570247|WD=Q11570247|1=Gozu Tennō}} Shrine, is also held lively<ref name="official"/><ref name="kanko">[https://www.miyakejima.gr.jp/see/osyakujinja/ Oshaku Shrine] - Miyakejima Tourism Association</ref><ref name="miyake">[https://www.soumu.metro.tokyo.lg.jp/14miyake/miyakehp/kankousasshi_0503.pdf Miyakejima (pp.66-68, p.84)] - Tokyo Metropolitan Government / Miyakejima Tourism Association</ref>.

=== Enshrined deity ===
* Sakitamahime-no-Mikoto (さきたまひめのみこと) - one of the consort deities of {{ill|UNKNOWN|WD=Q8009611|lt=Kotoshironushi-no-Kami|1=Kotoshironushi-no-Mikoto}} (Mishima Daimyōjin).

According to the mythology in ''Miyake-ki'', the three sister consorts of Mishima Daimyōjin (Kotoshironushi-no-Kami), worshiped at shrines on Miyakejima, were daughters of an old couple living around {{ill|lt=Hakone|Q11603342|WD=Q11603342|1=Hakone}} and {{ill|lt=Lake Ashi|Q187053|WD=Q187053|1=Lake Ashi}}, rescued from a dragon (great serpent) and brought to Miyakejima. The eldest is Igamuhime-no-Mikoto at {{ill|lt=Kisaki Shrine (Miyake Village)|Q134930558|WD=Q134930558|lt=Kisaki Shrine|1=Kisaki Shrine}}, the second is Iwanohime-no-Mikoto at {{ill|lt=Ninomiya Shrine (Miyake Village)|Q134930277|WD=Q134930277|lt=Ninomiya Shrine|1=Ninomiya Shrine (Q134930277)}}, and the third is Sakitamahime-no-Mikoto at Oshaku Shrine<ref name="chosa-miyake">[http://engishiki.org/izu/bun/iz149900-01.html Shrines of Miyakejima] - Survey of Engishiki Shrines</ref>.

=== Cultural properties ===
*Rituals of Oshaku Shrine (Tokyo-designated Intangible Folk Cultural Property, designated February 21, Shōwa 32)<ref name="都">[https://bunkazai.metro.tokyo.lg.jp/jp/search_detail.html?page=1&id=501 Rituals of Oshaku Shrine] Tokyo.</ref>

=== Access ===
*16 minutes by car from Sabigahama Port.

